<h2>The Midnight Broadcast</h2>
<p>
    During a power outage in the province, Nico used an old battery-powered television his father kept in storage. Most channels showed static, but one unfamiliar station suddenly appeared at exactly midnight. The screen displayed a dimly lit room containing only a wooden chair and a hanging light bulb swaying slowly. A voice from the television calmly announced, “Tonight’s guest has not arrived yet.” Nico laughed nervously, assuming it was some bizarre local program.
</p>
<br>
<p>
    After several minutes, the broadcast changed to grainy footage of Nico’s own street outside his house. The camera slowly moved closer toward his front gate as if someone were filming live. His laughter faded immediately when the television showed the inside of his home through the living room window. Then the voice returned and said, “Our guest is preparing to watch.” Nico turned off the television, but the screen remained glowing faintly in the darkness.
</p>
<br>
<p>
    Suddenly, the program displayed Nico sitting on the couch exactly where he was, except the version on-screen looked terrified. The television Nico watched in the broadcast showed another version of the same room repeating endlessly deeper into the screen. In each layer, something tall and black stood a little closer behind him. Nico slowly turned around and saw nothing in the darkness of his living room. But from the dead television came a final burst of static and a whisper: “You looked too early.”
</p>